TTH(1)                TeX to HTML translator               TTH(1)


@{B}NAME@{UB}@{UU}
       tth,  latex2gif,  ps2gif,  ps2png  - TeX and LaTeX to HTML
       translator and its auxiliary program

@{B}SYNOPSIS@{UB}@{UU}
       @{B}tth@{UB}@{UU} [@{U}options@{UB}@{UU}] [@{U}<file.tex@{UB}@{UU}] [@{U}>file.html@{UB}@{UU}] [@{U}2>err@{UB}@{UU}]

       @{B}tth@{UB}@{UU} [@{U}options@{UB}@{UU}] @{U}file.tex@{UB}@{UU} [@{U}2>err@{UB}@{UU}]

       @{B}latex2gif@{UB}@{UU} @{U}file@{UB}@{UU} (no extension)

       @{B}ps2gif@{UB}@{UU} @{U}file.ps@{UB}@{UU} @{U}file.gif@{UB}@{UU} [@{U}icon.gif@{UB}@{UU}]

       @{B}ps2png@{UB}@{UU} @{U}file.ps@{UB}@{UU} @{U}file.gif@{UB}@{UU} [@{U}icon.gif@{UB}@{UU}]

@{B}DESCRIPTION@{UB}@{UU}
       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} translates TeX source that uses the plain macro  pack-
       age  or  LaTeX,  including  most  mathematics, into a near
       equivalent in HTML. The formal  standard  that  TTH-trans-
       lated documents follow is strictly HTML4.0 Transitional.

       The  complete  documentation  is  contained  in  "tth_man-
       ual.html" distributed with the program. This man  page  is
       an  incomplete  summary and updated on an irregular basis.
       [Last updated 1 May 2002 by Hans Fredrik Nordhaug.]

       The program is a filter, i.e. it reads from standard input
       and  writes  to  standard  output. In addition, diagnostic
       messages concerning its detection of unknown  or  untrans-
       lated constructs are sent to standard error.

       In  handling  embedded graphical files @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} can make use of
       auxiliary programs,  @{U}ps2gif@{UB}@{UU} or @{U}ps2png@{UB}@{UU}, which in turn  make
       use of the ghostscript interpreter @{U}gs@{UB}@{UU} (1) and the Portable
       Bitmap Graphics suite of commands, see @{U}pbm@{UB}@{UU} (1).

       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} is extremely fast in default mode  on  any  reasonable
       hardware.   Conversion of even large TeX files should be a
       matter of a second or two.  This makes it possible to  use
       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  in  a  CGI  script  to  output HTML directly from TeX
       source if desired; (standard error may  then  need  to  be
       redirected.)

       To discuss how to get the best from @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}, you can subscribe
       to a mailing list by sending an email containing the  mes-
       sage  subscribe  tth_mailing_list  to  "majordomo@hutchin-
       son.belmont.ma.us".   Then  you  can  send   messages   to
       "tth_mailing_list@hutchinson.belmont.ma.us".

       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} handles TeX things like:
          Almost all mathematics, including symbols, fractions, delimiters.
          {} \\begingroup\\endgroup  grouping.
          \\it \\bf \\sl etc  styles.
          \\beginsection.



3.10                        1 May 2002                          1





TTH(1)                TeX to HTML translator               TTH(1)


          \\centerline{}.
          \\item{...} \\itemitem{...} {\\obeylines  ...}.
          Almost all accented latin characters written like \\"o, or \\"{e}.
          \\hang \\hangindent \\narrower for entire paragraphs
            (\\hangafter ignored).
          \\headline is made into a title.
          % Comments. Simply removed.
          \\halign tables, checks template for the presence of \\vrule,
            to decide if the table is to be border style.
          \\settabs \\+ style tables.
          \\input: But, of course, not from the implicit texinputs path.
          \\newcount, \\number, \\advance and counter setting.
          \\def, \\edef, \\xdef but no delimited arguments.
            All definitions are global.
          \\matrix, \\pmatrix but not \\bordermatrix. \\cases.

       LaTeX  support  includes  essentially all mathematics plus
       the following environments:
          em, verbatim, center, flushright [one paragraph  only],
          verse,  quotation,  quote, itemize, enumerate, descrip-
          tion, list [treated as if description], figure,  table,
          tabular[*,x], equation, displaymath, eqnarray [only one
          equation   number],   math,   array,   thebibliography,
          [raw]html, index [as description].
       and Latex commands:
          [re]newcommand,  newenvironment  [optional arg not per-
          mitted], chapter, section,  subsection,  subsubsection,
          caption, label, ref, pageref [no number], emph, textit,
          texttt, textbf, centering, raggedleft, includegraphics,
          [e]psfig, title, author, date [not automatic], lefteqn,
          frac, tableofcontents, input, include [as input], text-
          color,  color  [8  standard colors], footnote [ignoring
          optional arg], cite, bibitem,  bibliography,  tiny  ...
          normalsize  ...  Huge,  newcounter  [no ``within'' sup-
          port], setcounter, addtocounter, value [inside  set  or
          addto  counter],  arabic,  the,  stepcounter,  newline,
          verb[*], bfseries, itshape, ttfamily,  textsc,  ensure-
          math,   listoftables,   listoffigures,  newtheorem  [no
          optional arguments permitted], today, printindex, bold-
          math, unboldmath, newfont, thanks, makeindex, index.

       Hypertext  cross-references  within the document are auto-
       matically generated by (e.g.) ref, and tableofcontents.

       When @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} encounters TeX constructs that it  cannot  handle
       either  because there is no HTML equivalent, or because it
       is not clever enough, it tries to  remove  the  mess  they
       would otherwise cause in the HTML code, generally giving a
       warning of the action if it is not sure what it is  doing.
       Untranslatable TeX math tokens are inserted verbatim.

@{B}Independence@{UB}@{UU} @{B}of@{UB}@{UU} @{B}[La]TeX@{UB}@{UU} @{B}installation@{UB}@{UU} @{B}and@{UB}@{UU} @{B}the@{UB}@{UU} @{B}-L@{UB}@{UU} @{B}switch@{UB}@{UU}
       A  major difference between @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} and @{U}latex2html@{UB}@{UU} is that @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}
       does not call the @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU} or @{U}tex@{UB}@{UU} programs at all by default,



3.10                        1 May 2002                          2





TTH(1)                TeX to HTML translator               TTH(1)


       and  is  not  specifically dependent upon these, or indeed
       any other (e.g. @{U}perl@{UB}@{UU}), programs  being  installed  on  the
       translating  system.   Its portability is therefore virtu-
       ally universal.

       Forward references in LaTeX are handled by multiple passes
       that  write  auxiliary  files. @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} does only a single pass
       through the source.  If you want @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  to  use  LaTeX  con-
       structs  (e.g.  tableofcontents,  bibliographic  commands,
       etc.) that depend on auxiliary files, then you do need  to
       run  LaTeX  on the code so that these files are generated.
       Alternatively, the @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} switch -a causes @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  automatically
       to  attempt to run @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU} on the file, if no auxiliary file
       .aux exists.

       When run specifying a filename on the command  line  as  a
       non-switch  argument,  x  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  constructs  the name of the
       expected auxiliary LaTeX files in the usual way and  looks
       for  them  in  the same directory as the file.  If you are
       using @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  as a filter, you must  tell  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  ,  using  the
       switch  -Lfilename,  the base file name of these auxiliary
       files (which is the name of the original file omitting the
       extension).  If  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}   cannot  find the relevant auxiliary
       file because you didn't run LaTeX and generate  the  files
       or  didn't  include the switch, then it will omit the con-
       struct and warn you.  Forward references via ref will  not
       work  if the .aux file is unavailable, but backward refer-
       ences will. The -L switch with no filename may be used  to
       tell  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}   that  the  document  being translated is to be
       interpreted as a LaTeX file even though it lacks the usual
       LaTeX  header commands. This may be useful for translating
       single equations that (unwisely) use the \\frac command.

@{B}BibTeX@{UB}@{UU} @{B}bibliographies@{UB}@{UU}
       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} supports bibliographies that are created by hand using
       \\begin{thebibliography}  etc.  Such  bibliographies do not
       require anything beyond the .aux file. @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  also  supports
       bibliographies  created  using  BibTeX  from a biblography
       database. The filename.bbl file is input  at  the  correct
       place  in the document.  However, this filename.bbl is not
       created automatically by @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU}.  In  addition  to  running
       @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU} on the source file to create the auxiliary file, you
       must also execute bibtex filename in the  same  directory,
       to  create the filename.bbl file, and then run @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU} again
       to get the references right. (This is, of course, no  more
       than  the  standard  procedure for using @{U}bibtex@{UB}@{UU} with @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU}
       but it must be done if you want @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} to get your bibliogra-
       phy right). If you don't create the
        .bbl  file,  or if you create it somewhere else that  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}
       does not search, then naturally  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} won't find it.  Since
       the  BibTeX process is relatively tortuous,  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} offers an
       alternative. Using the -a switch with  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} will  cause  it
       to  attempt  to  generate the required .bbl file automati-
       cally using @{U}bibtex@{UB}@{UU} and @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU}.



3.10                        1 May 2002                          3





TTH(1)                TeX to HTML translator               TTH(1)


       There are many different styles for bibliographies  and  a
       large  number  of  different  LaTeX extension packages has
       grown up to implement them, which @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  does  not  support.
       More recently, a significant rationalization of the situa-
       tion has been achieved by the  package  natbib.   @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  has
       rudimentary  support  built in for its commands \\citep and
       citet in the default author-date  form  without  a  second
       optional argument.  A style file for natbib is distributed
       with TTHgold which makes it possible to  accommodate  most
       of  its  more useful styles and commands and easily switch
       from author-date citation to numeric citation.

@{B}Indexing@{UB}@{UU}
       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} can make an extremely useful hyperlinked  index  using
       LaTeX  automatic  indexing  entries.  But indexing an HTML
       document is different from indexing  a  printed  document,
       because a printed index refers to page numbers, which have
       no meaning in HTML because there are no page  breaks.  TTH
       indexes  LaTeX  documents by section number rather than by
       page; assuming, of course, that they  have  been  prepared
       with index entries in the standard LaTeX fashion.

       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  will  construct  an index based on the standard LaTeX
       commands "\\makeindex" and "\\index{...}", and automatically
       process  it  and  read it in when "\\printindex" is encoun-
       tered. The command line for calling the makeindex  program
       (not  part  of this distribution) may be changed using the
       @{U}-x@{UB}@{UU} switch. For a file without  the  "\\makeindex"  command,
       tth  will  write  no index files, just read in an existing
       one "file.ind" if it exists.

@{B}Graphics@{UB}@{UU} @{B}inclusion:@{UB}@{UU} @{B}epsfbox/includegraphics@{UB}@{UU}
       The standard way in plain TeX  to  include  a  graphic  is
       using  the  epsf  macros.  The  work  is  done  by  \\epsf-
       box{file.ps} which @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} can parse. By default @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  produces
       a  simple  link  to  such a postscript file, or indeed any
       format file.

       Optionally TTH can use a more appropriate graphics format,
       by  using  @{U}ps2gif@{UB}@{UU} or @{U}ps2png@{UB}@{UU} to convert the postscript file
       to a png or gif file, "file.png"  or  file.gif"  When  the
       switch   -e1   or   -e2  is  specified,  if  ``file.png'',
       ``file.gif'' or ``file.jpg'' already exists  in  the  same
       directory  as implied by the reference to ``file.ps'' then
       no conversion is done and the file found is used  instead.
       That  graphics  file  is  then automatically either linked
       (-e1) or inlined (-e2) in the document. If no such file is
       found,  TTH tries to find a postscript file with extension
       that starts either .ps or .eps and convert it, first using
       ps2png  then, if unsuccessful, ps2gif. By popular request,
       a third graphics option -e3 for generating  icons  is  now
       available.

       The  LaTeX  command  \\includegraphics{...}  and  the older



3.10                        1 May 2002                          4





TTH(1)                TeX to HTML translator               TTH(1)


       \\[e]psfig{file=...} are  treated  the  same  as  \\epsfbox.
       Their optional arguments are ignored.

@{B}Picture@{UB}@{UU} @{B}Environments@{UB}@{UU}
       The picture environment cannot be translated to HTML. Pic-
       tures using the built-in LaTeX commands must be  converted
       to a graphics file such as a gif or png, and then included
       using \\includegraphics.  The  switch  -a,  causes  @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  to
       attempt automatic picture conversion using @{U}latex2gif@{UB}@{UU}.

@{B}OPTIONS@{UB}@{UU}
       @{B}-a@{UB}@{UU}     attempt  automatic  conversion  of picture environ-
              ments. Default omit.

       @{B}-c@{UB}@{UU}     prefix header "Content-type: text/HTML" (for direct
              web serving).

       @{B}-d@{UB}@{UU}     disable   definitions   with  delimited  arguments.
              Default enable.

       @{B}-e@{UB}@{UU}?    epsfbox handling: @{B}-e1@{UB}@{UU}  convert  figure  to  png/gif
              using user-supplied ps2png/ps2gif.  @{B}-e2@{UB}@{UU} convert and
              include inline.  @{B}-e2@{UB}@{UU} as  e2  but  with  icon.   @{B}-e0@{UB}@{UU}
              (default) no conversion, just ref.

       @{B}-f@{UB}@{UU}?    sets  the  depth of grouping to which fractions are
              constructed built-up @{B}f5@{UB}@{UU} (default) allows five  lev-
              els built-up, @{B}f0@{UB}@{UU} none, @{B}f9@{UB}@{UU} lots.

       @{B}-g@{UB}@{UU}     don't  guess  an  HTML  equivalent for font defini-
              tions, just remove.

       @{B}-h@{UB}@{UU}     print some help.  @{B}-?@{UB}@{UU}  print usage

       @{B}-i@{UB}@{UU}     use italic font for equations (like  TeX).  Default
              roman.

       @{B}-j?@{UB}@{UU}    use  index page length ?. Default 20 lines. -j sin-
              gle column.

       @{B}-Lfile@{UB}@{UU} tells @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} the base file (no  extension)  for  LaTeX
              auxiliary input.

       @{B}-n?@{UB}@{UU}    HTML  title format control. 0 raw. 1 expand macros.
              2 expand eqns.

       @{B}-ppath@{UB}@{UU} specify additional directories (path) to search for
              input files.

       @{B}-r@{UB}@{UU}     output  raw  HTML  (no  preamble  or  postlude) for
              inclusion in other HTML.

       @{B}-t@{UB}@{UU}     permit  built-up  items  in  textstyle   equations.
              Default in-line items only.



3.10                        1 May 2002                          5





TTH(1)                TeX to HTML translator               TTH(1)


       @{B}-u@{UB}@{UU}     unicode character encoding. (Default iso-8859-1).

       @{B}-v@{UB}@{UU}     give verbose commentary.

       @{B}-V@{UB}@{UU}     even more verbose (for debugging).

       @{B}-w?@{UB}@{UU}    HTML  writing  style. Default no head/body tags. -w
              -w0 no title.  -w1  single  title  only,  head/body
              tags. -w2 XHTML.

       @{B}-xmakindxcmd@{UB}@{UU}
              specify a non-standard makeindex command line.

       @{B}-y?@{UB}@{UU}    equation  style:  bit  1 compress vertically; bit 2
              inline overaccents.


@{B}SEE@{UB}@{UU} @{B}ALSO@{UB}@{UU}
       The tth manual which is  more  likely  to  be  up-to-date.
       @{B}http://hutchinson.belmont.ma.us/tth/manual.cgi@{UB}@{UU} (or prefer-
       ably your local copy). In addition reading the  man  pages
       for  @{U}latex@{UB}@{UU}, @{U}latex2html@{UB}@{UU}, @{U}tex@{UB}@{UU} and @{U}makeindex@{UB}@{UU} might be useful.

@{B}Browser@{UB}@{UU} @{B}Problems@{UB}@{UU}
       @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU}  translates  (La)TeX  into  standard  HTML  and  takes
       account  as  far  as possible of the idiosyncrasies of the
       major browsers. Nevertheless, there are  several  problems
       that  are  associated  with the browsers. Authors and pub-
       lishers should recognize that these are not @{U}tth@{UB}@{UU} bugs.

       Many of the most serious difficulties of Mathematics  ren-
       dering in HTML are associated with the need for extra sym-
       bols. In addition to various Greek letters and  mathemati-
       cal  operators,  one  needs  access  to the glyphs used to
       build up from parts the large brackets matching the height
       of  built-up  fractions.  These symbols are almost univer-
       sally present on systems with  graphical  browsers,  which
       all  have  a ``Symbol'' font, generally based on that made
       freely available by Adobe. The problem lies  in  accessing
       the  font  because of shortcomings in the browsers and the
       HTML standards that relate to font use.

       For more information  please  read  the  section  "Browser
       Problems" in the manual.

